    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so basically concrete handles the weight pushing down on it, and the steel handles the pulling/stretching forces. does the placement of the rebar matter? like, do you just throw it in there randomly or is there a specific reason it has to be deep inside the slab instead of near the surface?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, placement is absolutely critical because rebar in the center of a beam is often called the \"tension zone,\" where it must stay away from the concrete surface to prevent accidental damage during pouring. If you place it too close to the edge, those high-stress areas might crack and expose the steel to the elements, leading to rust and structural failure. Think of it like placing a safety net in the middle of a trampoline where the action happens, rather than letting it hang loosely at the very top or bottom. Proper spacing ensures the steel is perfectly positioned to catch any internal tension before the concrete fails.",
      "source": "target",
